  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's a broad overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices existed in ancient civilizations\n- Formal legal frameworks began developing in the 20th century\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major US legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970) - Expanded legal tools to combat organized crime\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n\n3. International Developments:\n- Vienna Convention (1988) - Established international cooperation against drug trafficking proceeds\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Palermo Convention (2000) - Expanded international legal frameworks against organized crime\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded AML and counterterrorism financing regulations\n- Enhanced international information sharing and reporting requirements\n\n5. Ongoing Global Enforcement:\n- Continuous refinement of legal frameworks\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Growing technological sophistication in detecting financial crimes",
